field_data.Author: Scott
field_data.Sample Name: Scott11, 7nm NiFe NP's on Au, 22% coverage
field_data.Electrolyte: 0.1 M KOH, 0.1 M KOH in H2(18)O

notes: 01... weird behavior of M2 during mount. Beautiful CV's, Stable after 20 cycles. But... Position of Ni ox peak shifts anodic for lower cathodic potential limit, and OER activity seems to increase. Maybe just more time between cycles? No change of reduction peak position or area. M32 falling. Chip breaches! New chip installed, left to pump during lunch. 02... and again in O18! Electrolyte is 4.0 ul solK in 0.5 ml H2(18)O. 16000s in QMS. Much less active than earlier. Need to go to 0.2 V vs RE instead of 0.15, and still get less current. M34/M36 ratio is identical in first two cycles!!!! :D Redox peaks also shifted anodic vs RE relative to O16 electrolyte. Why??? Need H2 on system so we can calibrate RE in small volumes. None of the same effects of changing cathodic potential limit. 03... nice calibration down to 1 uA. No signal at 0.5 uA. 04... cycles look almost the same, a bit less area, OER as 02... 19800s, removed syringe from inlet. Whoa! Huge air signal at 20400s. Electrode shows no change, nor does OER at M36. Bubble over membrane but not over chip? Doesn't look like it, inlet and outlet holes still full of electrolyte. Chip cracked? Kept cycling. Increased anodic potential limit to 0.25 vs RE. Dumb, perhaps, as maybe isotope exchange is potential-dependent and we now have a bad background at M34 due to air signal. Stopped, rinsed 5x in drops of O18 water, and gave to Jakob. In air about 10 minutes between then and pumping of loadlock. In vacuum at 16:06. 23000s: The chip passes breath and drop test flying colors. No crack apparently.
